# .python-version
# pipenv
#   According to pypa/pipenv#598, it is recommended to include Pipfile.lock in version control for applications to ensure consistent dependency resolution across different environments and deployments. This is especially recommended for binary packages to ensure that the exact same versions of dependencies are used, which can be crucial for reproducibility and avoiding "works on my machine" issues. However, if your project is a library intended to be used in various environments, you might choose to ignore it to allow users to manage their own dependencies.
#   However, in case of collaboration, if having platform-specific dependencies or if the project is intended to be run in multiple environments, it might be better to ignore Pipfile.lock to allow each developer to generate their own based on the Pipfile, ensuring that they can install the appropriate dependencies for their specific environment. This is because, due to platform-specific dependencies and the fact that pipenv does not have cross-platform support, the Pipfile.lock file may contain different dependency versions for different platforms, which can lead to issues when sharing it across different environments. However, for applications where consistent dependency resolution is crucial, including Pipfile.lock in version control is generally recommended to ensure that all developers and deployment environments use the same versions of dependencies.
#   having no cross-platform support, pipenv may install dependencies differently on different platforms, which can lead to issues when sharing the Pipfile.lock file. In such cases, it might be better to ignore it and allow each developer to generate their own Pipfile.lock file based on the Pipfile, ensuring that they can install the appropriate dependencies for their specific environment. However, for applications where consistent dependency resolution is crucial, including Pipfile.lock in version control is generally recommended to ensure that all developers and deployment environments use the same versions of dependencies.
#   install all needed dependencies.
#Pipfile.lock
# poetry
#   Similar to Pipfile.lock, it is generally recommended to include poetry.lock in version control for applications to ensure consistent dependency resolution across different environments and deployments.
#   This is especially recommended for binary packages to ensure that the exact same versions of dependencies are used, which can be crucial for reproducibility and avoiding "works on my machine" issues. However, if your project is a library intended to be used in various environments, you might choose to ignore it to allow users to manage their own dependencies.
#   commonly ignored for libraries.
#   https://python-poetry.org/docs/basic-usage/#commit-your-poetrylock-file-to-version-control
#poetry.lock
